<h3>
    <strong>1. Sandy River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Just east of Gresham, this river is a hotspot for <strong>Chinook and Coho salmon</strong>, especially in <strong>spring and fall</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Spring Chinook arrive <strong>March–May</strong>, fall Chinook and Coho typically run <strong>September–October</strong> 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best access</strong>: Oxbow Regional Park, Glen Otto Community Park, Dodge Park, Cedar Creek near Troutdale&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Columbia River (Troutdale / Lower Gorge section)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Prime for <strong>spring/summer Chinook</strong>, <strong>fall Chinook</strong>, and <strong>Coho</strong>, with abundant runs and trophy-class fish 
    </li>
    <li>
        Launch from I‑84/Troutdale ramps or fish from shore near the mouth of Sandy River
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Clackamas River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Offers strong Coho and Chinook fishing in <strong>fall (September–October)</strong>, along with steelhead.
    </li>
    <li>
        Great access at Carver Park, Riverside Park, and Barton Park&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
