<h2>
    Key Access Points
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy River</strong>: Oxbow, Glen Otto, Dodge, Cedar Creek – great for bank fishing and wading
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River</strong>: Launch near Troutdale, Sauvie Island, or shore fishing near river mouths 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Clackamas River</strong>: Carver Park, Riverside Park, and Eagle Creek&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Tips for a Successful Salmon Trip
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Choose the right gear</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                Trolling with <strong>flashers and herring</strong> or using <strong>spinners and plugs</strong> near the mouth areas 
            </li>
            <li>
                For bank fishing, <strong>back-bouncing spinners</strong> on the Sandy or Clackamas rivers work well 
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Check water conditions</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                Coho thrive with cooler temps and rising water in early fall.
            </li>
            <li>
                Spring Chinook prefer higher flows, especially in Sandy and Willamette.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Know licensing and regulations</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                You’ll need an <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong>, <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong>, and <strong>Columbia River Endorsement</strong> for salmon/steelhead in these waters 
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best times of day</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                Dawn through mid-morning and late afternoon tend to bring more bites.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>
<h2>
    Family-Friendly &amp; Scenic Sites
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oxbow Regional Park</strong> on Sandy River: fishing, hiking, picnic areas – excellent for families outdoors
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Glen Otto Community Park</strong>: easy access and shallow gravel bars ideal for kids 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Carver Park (Clackamas)</strong>: paved trails and riverbank casting&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Guided Trips &amp; Local Shops
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Guided salmon trips</strong> frequently depart from Portland and Troutdale—options include Columbia River Chinook and Salmon &amp; Steelhead combos
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Local tackle destinations</strong>: Fisherman’s Marine, Sportsman’s Warehouse, and Troutdale bait shops—great for up-to-date run and tide info.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Final Take
</h2>
<p>
    Gresham anglers are fortunate to have world-class salmon waters – <strong>Sandy</strong>, <strong>Clackamas</strong>, and the <strong>Columbia</strong> rivers are all within 30 minutes. Springers, summer kings, fall Chinook, and Coho runs provide action from early spring through late fall. To maximize success, pay attention to seasonal patterns, use appropriate gear, secure the right licenses, and pick your spots wisely.
</p>
